## Skylight for Background Jobs (Beta)

While Skylight was originally designed to profile web requests, we understand that the web interface is only a part of your server-side application. We developed Skylight for Background Jobs in order to help you discover and correct hidden performance issues in your Sidekiq, DelayedJob, and ActiveJob queues.

<%= render partial: "note", locals: {
  note: <<~NOTE
          Skylight for Background Jobs is currently available as a #{link_to("beta", "./faqs/#accessing-user-interface-beta-features")}
          feature to Skylight Insiders. As an app owner, you must subscribe to Insiders before activating the background jobs feature in
          the agent.
        NOTE
}%>

### Beta Caveats

We are still working through some `TODO`s for background jobs, so there are some limitations to the feature in its current state. These include:
* We currently support jobs running via ActiveJob (with most backend frameworks), or Sidekiq and Delayed::Job as standalone processors. Click <%= link_to "here", "#probes" %> for a full list.
* Currently, jobs running over four hours will not be tracked (we have incrementally raised this limit and are still investigating the potential effects of raising it further).
* Jobs and requests with more than 2,048 items in the event sequence will result in "pruned" traces. In the job view in the UI, you may see nodes with the description "exceeded the maximum number of events allowed by the Skylight agent," which means that some nodes where dropped from the trace before it was submitted. You can read more about this limitation <%= link_to "here", "./troubleshooting#e0003-exceeded-maximum-number-of-spans" %>. Typically, you would see this error for individual jobs that do a lot of repetitive work--- we generally recommend splitting these up so one job instance performs one unit of work.

